body:
Hi @scordio , 
The issue seems to come from the fact that the values in the Json are transformed into `IntNode`s and `TextNode`s.  
Both those classes are extending`ValueNode`, extending`BaseJsonNode`, extending `JsonNode`, implementing `Iterable<JsonNode>`.

And because it implements `Iterable` the comparison gets caught by [if (dualValue.isExpectedFieldAnIterable()) in RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator](https://github.com/assertj/assertj-core/blob/main/src/main/java/org/assertj/core/api/recursive/comparison/RecursiveComparisonDifferenceCalculator.java#L252) instead of going through.

If we modify `DualValue` `isExpectedFieldAnIterable()` this way:

```java
  public boolean isExpectedFieldAnIterable() {
    // Don't consider Path as an Iterable as recursively comparing them leads to a stack overflow, here's why:
    // Iterable are compared element by element recursively
    // Ex: /tmp/foo.txt path has /tmp as its first element
    // so /tmp is going to be compared recursively but /tmp first element is itself leading to an infinite recursion
    return expected instanceof Iterable && !(expected instanceof Path || expected instanceof ValueNode);
  }
```
the following test fails with the right message:
```java
import com.fasterxml.jackson.core.JsonProcessingException;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

class JsonTest {

  @Test
  void test() throws JsonProcessingException {
    ObjectMapper om = new ObjectMapper();

    JsonNode objectNode0 = om.readTree("{\"someNotImportantValue\":1,\"importantValue\":\"10\"}");
    JsonNode objectNode1 = om.readTree("{\"someNotImportantValue\":15,\"importantValue\":\"1\"}");

    assertThat(objectNode0).usingRecursiveComparison().isEqualTo(objectNode1);
  }
}
```
But that implies that the type `com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ValueNode` is known at runtime, which might be complex if we can't add the dependency.

Not a big fan of this kind of approach, but based on your requirements I think we could do something like:
```java
  public boolean isExpectedFieldAnIterable() {
    return expected instanceof Iterable && !(expected instanceof Path || isExpectedFieldAJsonValueNode());
  }

  private boolean isExpectedFieldAJsonValueNode() {
    return expected.getClass().getPackageName().contains("com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node")
           && (expected.getClass().getName().endsWith("TextNode") || expected.getClass().getName().endsWith("IntNode"));
  }
```
Or creating a new `public isExpectedFieldAnJsonValueNode()` that would be called before `isExpectedFieldAnIterable` and would handle those cases.  
Of course there will be limitations, like catching classes that extend `TextNode`, `IntNode` or other subtypes. And the list of classes  could get quite long - or we need to look into a blacklist, for `ArrayNode` and `ContainerNode` at least.

Yeah, it's a bit tricky because we don't want to add jackson as a dependency (test dependency is ok though).

I'm ok adding `isExpectedFieldAJsonValueNode()` as you suggested @temp-droid, maybe renaming as `isExpectedFieldAJsonNode` and checking for any `JsonNode` (potentially by checking if any superclass is a `JsonNode` to avoid hardcoding the list of `JsonNode` subclasses). 

@temp-droid, since you seem to be advanced in this issue, do you want to tackle it?

I can have a try at tackling it, yes. I'm wondering if we shouldn't also do something for `isActualFieldAnIterable`. 

I'm not sure about checking for `JsonNode`, wouldn't it be safer to only check on `ValueNode` objects? Because `JsonNode` could be iterables like `ContainerNode`, `ArrayNode`…

```java
  public boolean isExpectedFieldAJsonNode() {
    return hasSuperclass(expected, "com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.JsonNode");
  }

  private boolean hasSuperclass(Object obj, String superclassName) {
    Predicate<Class<?>> sameCanonicalName = superclass -> superclass.getCanonicalName().equals(superclassName);
    return getSuperclasses(obj.getClass()).stream().anyMatch(sameCanonicalName);
  }

  private List<Class<?>> getSuperclasses(Class<?> clazz) {
    if (clazz == null) {
      return Collections.emptyList();
    }

    List<Class<?>> superclasses = new ArrayList<>();
    Class<?> superclass = clazz.getSuperclass();
    while (superclass != null && superclass != Object.class) {
      superclasses.add(superclass);
      superclass = superclass.getSuperclass();
    }

    return superclasses;
  }
```

> What if we would try to get a type instance with `Class.forName("com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ValueNode")` and then use `isInstance()`, catching `CLassNotFoundException` as an indication that it's not a Jackson related instance?

Interesting way to get the same result without loops indeed!

```java
  public boolean isExpectedFieldAJsonValueNode() {
    try {
      Class<?> valueNodeClass = Class.forName("com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.node.ValueNode");
      return valueNodeClass.isInstance(expected);
    } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {
      // expected cannot be a ValueNode because the class could not be located
      return false;
    }
  }
```

> Maybe the new method name could be `isActualFieldAJsonValueNode`.

Just to be clear, `s/Actual/Expected/`?
